Transactions are critical when it comes to maintaining data consistency. They ensure that a series of operations either all succeed or all fail, preserving the database state. This is part of the ACID properties, specifically the atomicity property.

Here’s an example of a transaction in SQL:

```sql
BEGIN TRANSACTION;

UPDATE Accounts SET Balance = Balance - 100 WHERE AccountID = 1;
UPDATE Accounts SET Balance = Balance + 100 WHERE AccountID = 2;

-- If both updates succeed, commit the transaction
COMMIT;

-- If any update fails, roll back all changes
-- ROLLBACK;
```
